1
00:00:01,200 --> 00:00:02,600
What do you think
of Darren Jarvis?

2
00:00:02,760 --> 00:00:04,160
At CBS?

3
00:00:04,240 --> 00:00:05,594
He wants me to be
a correspondent.

4
00:00:05,680 --> 00:00:07,194
It's not
worth your time.

5
00:00:08,440 --> 00:00:10,079
What about Greer Fisher,
at MSNBC?

6
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:13,674
Stick to writing,
do TV on the side.

7
00:00:13,760 --> 00:00:15,479
You're more than
a talking head.

8
00:00:17,240 --> 00:00:18,435
How about <i>Slugline?</i>

9
00:00:18,560 --> 00:00:19,755
What's <i>Slugline?</i>

10
00:00:20,280 --> 00:00:24,069
If I said <i>Politico</i> wanted to
hire me, what would you say?

11
00:00:24,160 --> 00:00:25,833
I would say that
that piques my interest.

12
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:27,957
Six months from now,
<i>Slugline</i> will be

13
00:00:28,080 --> 00:00:30,037
what <i>Politico</i> was
a year and half ago.

14
00:00:30,200 --> 00:00:31,316
Everyone at <i>Politico</i>
reads it

15
00:00:31,400 --> 00:00:33,198
because <i>Slugline's</i> breaking
stories before they are.

16
00:00:33,280 --> 00:00:34,919
I wonder why I've
never heard of it.

17
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:36,036
Everyone's
a free agent.

18
00:00:36,120 --> 00:00:38,635
And they write whatever they
want, wherever they are.

19
00:00:38,720 --> 00:00:40,279
Most people write
from their phones.

20
00:00:40,360 --> 00:00:43,353
Well, if freedom and exposure
are what they're offering,

21
00:00:43,480 --> 00:00:46,314
I would say that is
a meeting worth taking.

22
00:00:46,680 --> 00:00:49,115
This Hammerschmidt
thing is blowing up.

23
00:00:49,200 --> 00:00:51,078
I think he might
get fired.

24
00:00:51,160 --> 00:00:52,560
There's got to be
a thousand tweets here...

25
00:00:52,640 --> 00:00:55,075
People defending me,
people trashing me.

26
00:00:55,200 --> 00:00:57,510
There's even a hashtag,
GoZoe.

27
00:00:57,600 --> 00:00:58,590
Hmm.

28
00:01:01,640 --> 00:01:02,630
Hey!

29
00:01:03,560 --> 00:01:04,630
We mustn't leave
any trails.

30
00:01:04,760 --> 00:01:05,796
All of my contacts
were in there.

31
00:01:05,880 --> 00:01:09,317
Then it's time for you
to get some new contacts.

32
00:01:13,280 --> 00:01:15,431
Don't worry. I'll get you a phone.
I'll get you two, in fact.

33
00:01:15,520 --> 00:01:17,557
One for work
and a burner for play.

34
00:01:17,680 --> 00:01:19,399
Expect them
this afternoon.

35
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:24,310
Oh, and... Go, Zoe.

36
00:03:36,600 --> 00:03:37,636
The reporter?

37
00:03:37,760 --> 00:03:38,796
Yes.

38
00:03:41,320 --> 00:03:42,834
Just this once?

39
00:03:46,720 --> 00:03:48,279
I'm not sure.

40
00:03:49,520 --> 00:03:51,432
What does she offer us?

41
00:03:52,680 --> 00:03:54,194
A mouthpiece,
when we need one.

42
00:03:54,280 --> 00:03:55,999
She's been
very useful so far.

43
00:03:56,360 --> 00:03:57,953
What does she want?
Access.

44
00:03:58,040 --> 00:03:59,918
A seat at the table.

45
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:02,071
Sounds like she's getting the
better side of the bargain.

46
00:04:03,280 --> 00:04:05,112
She can be controlled.

47
00:04:05,200 --> 00:04:06,680
Are you sure?

48
00:04:06,920 --> 00:04:08,195
She can.
I promise you.

49
00:04:09,880 --> 00:04:11,314
Okay, if you say so.

50
00:04:12,320 --> 00:04:13,879
The moment you
want me to end it...

51
00:04:13,960 --> 00:04:15,713
I know, Francis.

52
00:04:19,200 --> 00:04:20,839
I should get
ready for work.

53
00:04:34,840 --> 00:04:35,910
Hey...

54
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:38,310
I didn't think
you'd be in until later.

55
00:04:38,400 --> 00:04:40,039
This is your
agenda for the day.

56
00:04:40,200 --> 00:04:41,839
Here's your schedule
for the rest of the week.

57
00:04:41,920 --> 00:04:43,957
These are papers that need
to be approved or signed.

58
00:04:44,040 --> 00:04:46,032
Over here are your one-sheets
for committee meetings

59
00:04:46,120 --> 00:04:49,158
and briefs on upcoming
legislative action.

60
00:04:49,240 --> 00:04:52,233
I filled Ashley in. She can cover
until you find a replacement.

61
00:05:01,120 --> 00:05:02,349
Christina.

62
00:05:03,560 --> 00:05:04,676
What?

63
00:05:08,280 --> 00:05:09,680
Thank you.

64
00:05:10,160 --> 00:05:12,720
For getting
all this in order.

65
00:05:17,560 --> 00:05:21,440
Ashley can call me if you have any
questions about what's on your desk.

66
00:05:26,040 --> 00:05:27,076
He here yet?

67
00:05:27,200 --> 00:05:28,236
I put him
in your office.

68
00:05:33,920 --> 00:05:36,799
Marty Spinella. Head lobbyist
for the teachers union.

69
00:05:36,880 --> 00:05:39,315
He wants to rip my head off
and peel it like an orange.

70
00:05:39,440 --> 00:05:42,194
Why? Because I lied to him.
But what choice did I have?

71
00:05:42,320 --> 00:05:45,791
When the truth would have ended
the conversation before it began?

72
00:05:45,880 --> 00:05:47,553
I'll call you back.
Marty.

73
00:05:49,560 --> 00:05:51,313
You fucking lied, Frank?

74
00:05:51,400 --> 00:05:53,392
No, no, no.
You lie to my fucking face?

75
00:05:53,520 --> 00:05:55,352
Marty, I did not lie. What
do you mean you did not?

76
00:05:55,440 --> 00:05:57,113
We spent a whole
weekend in that room

77
00:05:57,280 --> 00:05:58,953
poring over this bill
line by line.

78
00:05:59,040 --> 00:06:01,874
And nowhere did it say anything
about collective bargaining.

79
00:06:01,960 --> 00:06:04,873
Let's calm down and sit down.
And we will discuss this.

80
00:06:04,960 --> 00:06:08,158
I will explain everything that's
going on and we will talk it out.

81
00:06:08,280 --> 00:06:09,873
No matter how long it takes.
No. No more.

82
00:06:09,960 --> 00:06:11,440
This is gonna be
a very short meeting.

83
00:06:11,520 --> 00:06:13,671
'Cause only one of two
things are going to happen.

84
00:06:13,800 --> 00:06:16,793
Either you assure me right
now that amendment is out,

85
00:06:16,880 --> 00:06:19,873
or I am walking out that door and I
am gonna start launching missiles.

86
00:06:19,960 --> 00:06:22,395
The amendment was never
intended to stay in the bill.

87
00:06:22,480 --> 00:06:23,800
It's just there for leverage.
That's all.

88
00:06:23,880 --> 00:06:27,715
You threaten to cut federal funding
from union school districts?

89
00:06:27,800 --> 00:06:30,634
That's not a poker chip, Frank,
that's a goddamn dirty bomb.

90
00:06:30,720 --> 00:06:34,873
Look, the amendment
is not staying in the bill.

91
00:06:36,200 --> 00:06:39,159
I just need you to work with
me on performance standards.

92
00:06:39,520 --> 00:06:40,749
Performance standards?

93
00:06:41,680 --> 00:06:44,195
Are you fucking kidding me? You
agreed that they were already out.

94
00:06:44,320 --> 00:06:46,198
You can't just put it back in now, Frank.
Marty, look...

95
00:06:46,280 --> 00:06:48,078
I have a reputation
to uphold.

96
00:06:48,160 --> 00:06:51,551
I am the one that made the
union reps stay here for you

97
00:06:51,680 --> 00:06:54,149
while you're in Gaffney playing
with your fucking Peachoid.

98
00:06:54,240 --> 00:06:55,356
Marty...
You tell me right now,

99
00:06:55,440 --> 00:06:57,113
is that amendment
in or out?

100
00:06:57,960 --> 00:07:01,840
There is a middle ground here, Marty.
We just have to find it.

101
00:07:03,920 --> 00:07:05,832
I take that as a no.

102
00:07:08,840 --> 00:07:10,069
Okay.

103
00:07:12,200 --> 00:07:15,750
Marty, do not start a war
you know you're gonna lose.

104
00:07:15,840 --> 00:07:17,957
You fuck me,
I fuck back.

105
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:24,150
Stamper!

106
00:07:24,240 --> 00:07:26,550
Marty and I have a good
working relationship.

107
00:07:26,640 --> 00:07:27,630
Or used to.

108
00:07:27,720 --> 00:07:28,870
You could see
he has a temper,

109
00:07:28,960 --> 00:07:31,111
but I can usually cut through
that and reason with him.

110
00:07:31,200 --> 00:07:34,352
But I may have pushed him too far.
Which is worrisome.

111
00:07:34,440 --> 00:07:36,750
Friends make
the worst enemies.

112
00:07:38,920 --> 00:07:40,752
How'd it go?
What'd you hear?

113
00:07:40,880 --> 00:07:43,952
A lot of fucks. Well,
that pretty much says it.

114
00:07:44,560 --> 00:07:45,880
Let's think
this through...

115
00:07:45,960 --> 00:07:47,189
No, we've got the DNC
leadership meeting.

116
00:07:47,400 --> 00:07:48,629
What?

117
00:07:48,720 --> 00:07:51,110
I'd say you could skip it, but
Birch just dumped it on us.

118
00:07:51,280 --> 00:07:53,556
When? It's here. In 12 minutes.

119
00:07:53,640 --> 00:07:55,313
Why here and not
the DNC headquarters?

120
00:07:55,440 --> 00:07:58,592
The DNC is doing renovations, they're
gonna be green-energy efficient.

121
00:07:58,680 --> 00:08:01,559
That's a charming
use of party funds.

122
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:04,310
We've only been in this
space about three months.

123
00:08:04,760 --> 00:08:05,910
It's cool.

124
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:07,878
Not exactly
<i>The Herald,</i> is it?

125
00:08:07,960 --> 00:08:10,555
Have you been to those offices?
Yes.

126
00:08:10,680 --> 00:08:12,831
Wrist-slitting
was in order.

127
00:08:13,240 --> 00:08:15,550
So, who else
is courting you?

128
00:08:16,080 --> 00:08:17,116
A few people.

129
00:08:17,240 --> 00:08:18,310
You mean everyone.

130
00:08:19,040 --> 00:08:20,679
There were a lot of
emails this morning...

131
00:08:20,760 --> 00:08:22,080
That's not surprising.

132
00:08:22,160 --> 00:08:24,629
You're having a moment,
people are interested.

133
00:08:24,720 --> 00:08:25,995
I'm one of them.

134
00:08:26,080 --> 00:08:28,754
But if eight minutes passes
on anything, I get bored.

135
00:08:28,880 --> 00:08:31,440
In eight minutes, I could be bored with you.
Unless you keep me interested.

136
00:08:32,840 --> 00:08:34,240
I think you can,

137
00:08:34,320 --> 00:08:35,674
and I think this
is the place for you

138
00:08:35,760 --> 00:08:37,911
to keep the rest of
the world interested, too.

139
00:08:38,320 --> 00:08:40,118
It's your call.
I won't chase you.

140
00:08:40,200 --> 00:08:41,554
I'm definitely tempted...

141
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:43,957
Take as long as you
want to look around.

142
00:08:44,040 --> 00:08:46,999
Email me your figure. I'll
call you back with a counter.

143
00:08:51,640 --> 00:08:55,953
This is our top priority. Ohio,
Florida and Pennsylvania.

144
00:08:56,720 --> 00:08:59,030
We need all of them or
Walker's a one-term president.

145
00:08:59,120 --> 00:09:01,715
Pennsylvania is why he picked
Matthews as a running mate.

146
00:09:01,800 --> 00:09:03,632
But now we have to
find a replacement.

147
00:09:03,760 --> 00:09:05,558
The special election
is this November.

148
00:09:06,120 --> 00:09:08,271
Patricia Whittaker.
DNC chair.

149
00:09:08,440 --> 00:09:10,875
A rare example of someone
whose head is in the game

150
00:09:10,960 --> 00:09:12,758
instead of
up their backside.

151
00:09:12,840 --> 00:09:15,116
Competence is such an
exotic bird in these woods

152
00:09:15,280 --> 00:09:17,556
that I appreciate
it whenever I see it.

153
00:09:17,640 --> 00:09:19,711
Now, this also
affects the House.

154
00:09:19,800 --> 00:09:21,473
The new Governor will
oversee redistricting.

155
00:09:21,560 --> 00:09:22,755
We lose seats here,

156
00:09:22,840 --> 00:09:24,320
that means we could lose
our majority in Washington.

157
00:09:24,640 --> 00:09:27,599
Well, the RNC is backing Jack
Swofford, ex-mayor of Pittsburgh.

158
00:09:27,680 --> 00:09:29,797
He's got state-wide
name recognition

159
00:09:29,920 --> 00:09:31,240
and campaign machinery
in place...

160
00:09:31,320 --> 00:09:34,392
It's been three months
and we don't have dick.

161
00:09:34,480 --> 00:09:36,278
What about the A.G.?
Ben Pluckett?

162
00:09:36,400 --> 00:09:38,835
No, Ben's got his eyes set
on the Senate in '14.

163
00:09:38,920 --> 00:09:42,038
Yeah, which he'll lose because he
botched a sex offender sting last year.

164
00:09:42,120 --> 00:09:44,510
Well, there's always McHolland.
He's 78.

165
00:09:44,600 --> 00:09:46,831
When's the last time he held office?
When Carter was president?

166
00:09:46,920 --> 00:09:48,832
Reagan,
but same difference.

167
00:09:48,920 --> 00:09:50,957
Well, he has dignity.
He has gravitas.

168
00:09:51,040 --> 00:09:52,599
I mean, if you need someone
to fill Matthews' shoes...

169
00:09:52,680 --> 00:09:55,400
You can't fill Jim Matthews' shoes.
So we shouldn't even try.

170
00:09:55,840 --> 00:09:57,399
We need a fresh face.

171
00:09:57,480 --> 00:09:58,994
The state has
a weak bench.

172
00:09:59,080 --> 00:10:01,356
Well, let's go through all the
sitting Congressmen one by one,

173
00:10:01,480 --> 00:10:02,800
and see if anybody
sticks out from the crowd.

174
00:10:02,920 --> 00:10:05,754
All right. I got the list right here.
Okay. Go ahead.

175
00:10:05,840 --> 00:10:08,480
Pennsylvania's first
district, Peter Russo.

176
00:10:08,560 --> 00:10:11,394
Cross him off. He's no good.
No experience. No chops.

177
00:10:11,480 --> 00:10:14,439
Okay, moving on. Second
district, Gwendolyn Pierce.

178
00:10:14,520 --> 00:10:17,479
Gwen's too controversial.
Very vocal on abortion...

179
00:10:17,560 --> 00:10:18,550
And, Caroline?

180
00:10:18,720 --> 00:10:19,756
She's good.

181
00:10:19,880 --> 00:10:20,870
Yeah? How're the boys?

182
00:10:21,040 --> 00:10:22,030
All fuckin'
four of them?

183
00:10:22,120 --> 00:10:23,873
You feed 'em.

184
00:10:23,960 --> 00:10:26,270
You got any pictures?
On your phone?

185
00:10:26,360 --> 00:10:28,477
Come on. Let's cut the
shit, Pete, will ya?

186
00:10:28,600 --> 00:10:30,717
What are we gonna do
about the shipyard?

187
00:10:34,040 --> 00:10:37,033
BRAC had their hearing.
They slated it for closing.

188
00:10:37,120 --> 00:10:39,316
Yeah, and why
didn't you testify?

189
00:10:39,440 --> 00:10:41,636
We're talking
12,000 jobs here.

190
00:10:41,720 --> 00:10:44,280
My hands were tied, Paul.
People wanted it closed.

191
00:10:44,400 --> 00:10:46,153
I was under a lot of pressure.
From who?

192
00:10:47,120 --> 00:10:49,237
People high up the food chain.
There's nothing I could do.

193
00:10:49,680 --> 00:10:52,957
That's bullshit. You go back to BRAC.
You talk to the DOD.

194
00:10:53,040 --> 00:10:55,396
You talk to the Secretary of the Navy.
You do something...

195
00:10:55,480 --> 00:10:56,470
It's not gonna happen.

196
00:10:56,600 --> 00:10:57,636
Okay, why not?

197
00:10:58,000 --> 00:10:59,354
I told you,
it's political.

198
00:10:59,440 --> 00:11:01,477
Okay, so I'm supposed to go back
to the Shipbuilder's Association

199
00:11:01,560 --> 00:11:02,835
and say what now,
exactly?

200
00:11:03,200 --> 00:11:05,840
That they're out of work because
Pete Russo's playing politics?

201
00:11:08,160 --> 00:11:09,389
I mean, Jesus, Pete.

202
00:11:09,840 --> 00:11:12,594
We're the ones who got you fuckin'
elected in the first place.

203
00:11:13,720 --> 00:11:16,110
Now you're gonna
turn your back on us?

204
00:11:16,200 --> 00:11:17,998
You should go.

205
00:11:20,080 --> 00:11:21,309
Seriously?

206
00:11:23,680 --> 00:11:25,717
I just got here.
You're kickin' me out now?

207
00:11:26,880 --> 00:11:29,600
Hey, I'm fuckin'
talkin' to you.

208
00:11:32,040 --> 00:11:33,759
I thought we
grew up together.

209
00:11:33,880 --> 00:11:37,430
But this guy, sitting
behind his big desk,

210
00:11:38,160 --> 00:11:41,119
I don't even know
who the fuck he is.

211
00:11:42,400 --> 00:11:44,073
Where's the Pete Russo who
knew how to throw a punch

212
00:11:44,160 --> 00:11:46,675
when his back was
against the wall?

213
00:11:46,880 --> 00:11:48,837
That guy was my friend.

214
00:12:01,520 --> 00:12:03,557
Every teacher in the country?
A month before school ends?

215
00:12:03,640 --> 00:12:04,676
He doesn't need
all of them.

216
00:12:04,760 --> 00:12:06,752
Fifteen, 20 states.
That's all.

217
00:12:06,840 --> 00:12:08,877
But the AFT and the NEA
can't agree on anything.

218
00:12:08,960 --> 00:12:10,997
You underestimate
Marty Spinella.

219
00:12:12,800 --> 00:12:14,154
So which one
do we target?

220
00:12:15,880 --> 00:12:17,109
We have a better
chance with the NEA.

221
00:12:17,880 --> 00:12:19,314
You think Chuck Sloan
will bite?

222
00:12:19,400 --> 00:12:22,552
Cooperate, we give your people
protection and a place at the banquet.

223
00:12:22,640 --> 00:12:24,359
Fight us, we break you.

224
00:12:24,480 --> 00:12:26,073
He'll bite.
Get him on the phone.

225
00:12:26,160 --> 00:12:27,196
It's after 2:00.

226
00:12:27,960 --> 00:12:30,600
Spinella's potentially mobilizing
the largest teachers' strike

227
00:12:30,680 --> 00:12:32,956
in United States history.
Nobody's sleeping.

228
00:12:33,040 --> 00:12:34,997
I'll call him
right now.

229
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:37,753
I'm sorry.
Are we being too loud?

230
00:12:37,840 --> 00:12:39,194
A little.

231
00:12:41,920 --> 00:12:42,956
What are you working on?

232
00:12:43,040 --> 00:12:45,191
The gala.
There's so much to do.

233
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:48,036
Did Nancy
send you my list?

234
00:12:48,200 --> 00:12:49,270
She did.

235
00:12:49,360 --> 00:12:51,113
And what'd you think?

236
00:12:51,480 --> 00:12:54,393
It's a good list.
Thanks for inviting them.

237
00:12:57,200 --> 00:12:58,680
Is something wrong?

238
00:13:01,120 --> 00:13:03,840
It's still not anywhere near
what Remy brought to the table.

239
00:13:05,400 --> 00:13:07,631
SanCorp offered
1.5 million, Francis.

240
00:13:07,720 --> 00:13:11,270
I'm adding up the numbers and
we're only at half a million.

241
00:13:11,360 --> 00:13:13,477
I got Chuck on the phone.
In a minute.

242
00:13:13,560 --> 00:13:14,596
I can make
more calls...

243
00:13:14,680 --> 00:13:16,034
Enough to raise
1.5 million?

244
00:13:16,640 --> 00:13:18,199
Well, I can at least
get us closer.

245
00:13:20,840 --> 00:13:22,035
